Document: GPUParticlesCollision3D  
Path: godot/classes/class_gpuparticlescollision3d.rst  
Summary: Class for GPU-based particle collision detection and interaction in 3D space.  

Inherits: Node3D < Spatial < Node < Object  
Key Rule: This class enables efficient collision detection between particles and 3D objects using GPU acceleration.  
Key Rule: Requires a GPUParticles3D node as a parent for proper functionality.  
Key Rule: Collision data is processed on the GPU to minimize CPU overhead.  
Key Rule: Supports collision filtering via layer masks and collision shape definitions.  
Key Rule: Collision events trigger signals for particle system interaction.  
Key Rule: Uses spatial hashing for optimized broad-phase collision detection.  
Key Rule: Collision response can be configured via physics material properties.  
Key Rule: Requires a valid PhysicsServer3D implementation for collision resolution.  
Key Rule: Collision data is updated in real-time during physics processing steps.  
Key Rule: Supports both static and dynamic collision object types.  
Key Rule: Collision detection is disabled by default and must be explicitly enabled.  
Key Rule: Collision shape can be customized via a separate CollisionShape3D node.  
Key Rule: Collision response strength is controlled via the "collision_response" parameter.  
Key Rule: Collision data is visualized in the editor using debug rendering modes.  
Key Rule: Collision detection is limited to convex shapes for performance reasons.  
Key Rule: Collision events are processed in the physics thread to avoid main thread blocking.  
Key Rule: Collision data is synchronized with the particle system's transform hierarchy.  
Key Rule: Collision detection is affected by the particle system's emission rate and lifespan.  
Key Rule: Collision response can be disabled per-particle via custom flags.  
Key Rule: Collision data is stored in a separate buffer to avoid particle system memory conflicts.  
Key Rule: Collision detection is compatible with both CPU and GPU physics processing modes.  
Key Rule: Collision events can be used to trigger particle system behavior changes.  
Key Rule: Collision detection is affected by the particle system's velocity and direction.  
Key Rule: Collision response can be adjusted per-collision using material properties.  
Key Rule: Collision data is accessible via the "get_collision_data()" method for advanced use.
