Document: GPUParticlesCollision3D  
Path: godot/classes/class_gpuparticlescollision3d.rst  
Summary: Particle collision shapes for real-time interaction with GPU particles, enabling stopping or bouncing effects.  

Particle collision shapes can be used to make particles stop or bounce against them. They work in real-time and can be moved, rotated, and scaled during gameplay. Non-uniform scaling of collision shapes is not supported. Collision shapes can be temporarily disabled by hiding them.  

Note: ParticleProcessMaterial.collision_mode must be ParticleProcessMaterial.COLLISION_RIGID or ParticleProcessMaterial.COLLISION_HIDE_ON_CONTACT on the GPUParticles3D's process material for collision to work.  

Note: Particle collision only affects GPUParticles3D, not CPUParticles3D.  

Note: Particles pushed by a collider that is being moved will not be interpolated, which can result in visible stuttering. This can be alleviated by setting GPUParticles3D.fixed_fps to 0 or a value that matches or exceeds the target framerate.
